<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article I</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The name of this organization shall be the Sierra Virginia Community, (hereinafter referred to as SVC).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center">Article II</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>SVC is a nonprofit membership association dedicated to advancing the growth and welfare of members of the community. Foster better community relationships through various social activities and receive gifts or donations to promote the interest of the Sierra Leone Virginia Community through sports.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article III</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 1</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Members are formed by the qualifications which shall be described as follows:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>(i) Adults. Adult members, both voting and non-voting, shall be persons: (a) who are twenty (20) years old or older; (b) who have executed and delivered to the Board an Association membership application for members, plus any other document requested by the Board in its sole opinion and whose membership has been approved by the Board in its sole opinion; (c) who agree to, and do, in fact, adhere to the constitution, the Bylaws and all other rules and regulations of the Association (the ‚ÄúRules and Regulations‚Äù), and (d) who have paid all dues and fees required by the Association</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 3</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Members must remain in good standing regarding payment of registration fees and their monthly dues of $20. Failure to do so will prevent offending members from participating in all community activities including but not limited to practicing with the soccer team, representing the team in competitions, receiving any form of financial contributions, getting community support for baby showers, weddings, etc, and participation in all the community‚Äôs various social media platforms.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 4</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Any members who wish to run for office or hold any financial position must be up to date with their monthly payments and financially fit. I.e., They should not have any pending or existing legal or financial litigation case against them, including but not limited to owning child support payment, wage garnishment, debt with a collection agency, ongoing legal case, or any legal or financial dispute that will have any legal or financial ramification on SVC.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 5</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Members will be limited to one financial contribution per year. For the following events/occasion<br>- Baby Shower<br>- Engagement or Weddings ‚Äì Members will only get financial contributions for one of these not both.<br>- Bereavement - limited to Mothers, Fathers, and Children<br>Any request for additional financial help or contribution during the same fiscal year will be determined by the executive and put to vote in a meeting to be decided by two-thirds of the members present at the meeting.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><br>New members who wish to join SVC after <strong>November 2021</strong> must pay his/her:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>The registration fee is $50<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>All monthly due up to the date he/she is registered*</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list --></li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 6</strong><br>Registered members who fail to pay their monthly dues for <strong>ONE YEAR </strong>but wants to re-join SVC will have to re-register and pay all past monthly contribution*</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 7</strong><br>Registered members who fail to pay their monthly dues for <strong>TWO YEARS</strong> and want to re-join SVC for the opportunity to participate in any elections will have to re-register and pay all past monthly dues, and their membership can only be reinstated by a two-thirds vote of the community.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Registered members who are a year behind in their monthly dues during an election year but want to fulfill their monthly dues so they can vote in an upcoming election will not be allowed to do so; any change to allow them to vote will require a two-thirds vote of the community during a meeting held by the seating president. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>*If the member has a valid reason for being inactive. He/she must submit a written explanation to the executive, who will present the findings to the members of SVC to decide if their membership can be reinstated by a two-thirds vote of the community</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 8</strong><br>Members can be <strong>temporarily</strong> removed from the SVC WhatsApp group for disciplinary issues or for not following the group's guidelines. NOTE: When a member is removed from the group, it does not mean they have been terminated or are no longer a member of SVC.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 9</strong><br>Only current registered members who are up-to-date with their monthly dues will be allowed or added to the SVC WhatsApp. Registered members who have not paid any dues after registering will be removed from WhatsApp and only added after all outstanding dues have been made.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 10</strong><br>Funds raised for members for a particular occasion/function must be used for that occasion. Members are not allowed to falsely request help for funds from SVC for any other use than the initial request. Any member guilty of such a fraudulent act will be dismissed from the community. &nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 11</strong><br>All monies for financial help or contribution will be paid out by the treasurer by check so that a record of the transaction will be on file The executive should approve any other form of payment. The payment will only be presented/handed over at the event or occasion by a member of the executive. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 12</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Membership may be terminated by a two-thirds vote of the eligible voters at a membership meeting.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article IV</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 1</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The Executive Body (hereinafter referred to as Officers) shall comprise three elected officers.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 2</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&nbsp;The following officers of SVC shall be elected every two years (2) as follows:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A. President<br>B. Coach<br>C. Team Manager<br>The President and Coach are responsible for picking their cabinet as they see fit. Including but not limited to:&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Vice President</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Secretary-General</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Asst. Secretary-General</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Treasurer</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Asst. Treasurer</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>PRO</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Asst. PRO</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Asst. Coach</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Asst. Team Managers</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 3</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>All elected officers shall be elected by the membership at the Annual Meeting by a majority vote of the members in attendance in the month of <strong>October</strong> on a date set by the seating president.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 4</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The duties of the elected and appointed officers shall be as follows:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>The President</strong> - The President of a community plays a central leadership role with diverse responsibilities aimed at advancing the well-being and interests of the community members. Their primary role includes setting a vision and strategic direction for the community, often in consultation with an elected board or council, and overseeing the execution of community initiatives and projects. They represent the community in dealings with external organizations, government bodies, and stakeholders, advocating for its needs and interests. The President is also typically responsible for managing community finances, allocating resources, and ensuring financial sustainability. Moreover, they often act as a unifying figure within the community, mediating disputes, fostering collaboration, and promoting unity among residents. Ultimately, the President of a community is responsible for shaping the community's future, enhancing its quality of life, and ensuring its overall growth and prosperity.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>The Treasurer</strong> - Oversee the Organization's Financial Administration. Review and Enforce Financial Policies and Procedures. Generate Financial Reports. Create a Budget Advise the Board on Financial Strategy and Fundraising. Financial reporting. Banking, bookkeeping, and record-keeping. All community income and expenditures, including payment and receipts of funds, should be recorded, accounted for, and made by the treasurer.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>The TM</strong> ‚Äì The Team Manager, shall be responsible for ensuring the smooth operation and success of the squad. Their responsibilities encompass various tasks, including player coordination, scheduling, and logistics management. They organize and oversee training sessions, matches, and travel arrangements, ensuring the team is well-prepared and punctual. Team managers also handle administrative duties such as player registrations, budget management, and communication with the community. Importantly, they serve as a bridge between coaching staff, players, and the club's management, fostering a positive team culture, resolving conflicts, and supporting players on and off the field. The Team Manager should be vital in creating an environment conducive to the team's success and unity.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>The Coach</strong> - The coach is pivotal in shaping a team's performance and nurturing player development. His responsibilities encompass many facets, including devising tactical strategies, drills, and game plans to optimize the team's performance. The coach is tasked with honing individual players' skills, improving their fitness levels, and instilling a solid work ethic. He is crucial in motivating and inspiring the team, providing constructive feedback, and fostering a cohesive team spirit. Additionally, the coach is responsible for making strategic in-game decisions, substitutions, and adjustments to adapt to evolving match situations. Beyond the field, he also serves as a mentor and role model, guiding players in soccer and life, instilling discipline, sportsmanship, and a passion for the game. The coach serves as the driving force behind a team's success, shaping its identity and helping players reach their full potential.<br><br><strong>The Vice President</strong> - The Vice President plays a critical supportive role to the President in overseeing and facilitating various aspects of community affairs. Their responsibilities often include assisting the President in setting strategic goals and priorities and, in their absence, assuming leadership duties. The Vice President may also oversee specific committees or initiatives within the community, such as events planning, fundraising, or community outreach efforts. The Vice President collaborates closely with the President to represent the community's interests to external stakeholders, participate in meetings, and support decision-making processes. Additionally, the Vice President often serves as a bridge between community members and leadership, helping to gather input, address concerns, and promote a sense of engagement and unity. The Vice President of a community plays a pivotal role in the effective governance and overall success of the community by providing invaluable assistance to the President and fostering community cohesion.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>The Secretary-General</strong> - The Secretary-General of a soccer team plays a pivotal behind-the-scenes role in managing the administrative and organizational aspects of the club. Their responsibilities span various tasks, including record-keeping, communication, and logistics management. They are responsible for maintaining accurate records of club meetings, managing club documentation, and ensuring compliance with regulations and guidelines set forth by governing bodies or regional soccer associations. The Secretary-General is often the primary point of contact for internal and external communications, liaising with stakeholders, sponsors, and other clubs. They also play a critical role in coordinating team logistics, including travel arrangements, venue bookings, and match scheduling. Overall, the Secretary-General is a key figure in ensuring the efficient and compliant operation of the community, enabling all the different community sections to focus on their performance.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>PRO</strong> - The (PRO) serves as the team's primary communicator and advocate, responsible for maintaining a positive public image and fostering strong community relationships. Their roles encompass a variety of tasks, including managing the team's social media presence, issuing press releases, and organizing community engagement events. The PRO plays a crucial role in promoting the team's activities, matches, and events, helping to build a loyal fan base and attract sponsors. They also handle media inquiries and interviews and work closely with local media outlets to ensure adequate coverage. Furthermore, the PRO may engage in outreach efforts, such as youth soccer clinics or charity initiatives, to strengthen ties between the team and the community. The Public Relations Officer is instrumental in building and maintaining a positive and supportive relationship between the community soccer team and its fans and supporters.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 5</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Any Officer failing to attend meetings in such a manner as to consistently cause a quorum to not be established shall have his continued tenure subjected to a vote of the membership in no less than ten nor more than thirty days from the last meeting of Officers where a quorum was not established. Any Officer may be removed from office by a two-thirds vote of the membership present at a membership meeting.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article V</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 1</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A Meeting of the membership shall be held at the call of the president, provided that at least one meeting be held monthly.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 2</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The meeting normally held in the month of October shall be called the annual meeting and shall be for the election of officers and presentation of the budget.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 3</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Two-thirds of community members who are current with their monthly contributions are needed to hold the election. The candidate with the most votes will determine the winner.        </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section </strong>4</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A quorum of Officers is required at all meetings to conduct business. A quorum is defined as three or more Officers present.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article VI</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Committees may be appointed as needed by the President with the advice and consent of the executive for an active life to be specified in the appointment.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article VII</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><br><strong>Section 1</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Each Officer shall have one vote, with the President voting only to break a tie.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Section 2</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Membership voting: each household shall have one vote.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article VIII</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><br>The fiscal year of SVC shall be from October 1st to September 31st the following year.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article IX</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A two-thirds vote of the members may amend these bylaws, provided that the amendment has been presented in writing at the previous meeting.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center"><strong>Article X</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The rules contained in the current edition of Roberts Rules of Order shall govern SVC in all cases in which they are applicable and do not conflict with these bylaws.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Article XI These bylaws shall be in effect as of the 1st day of November 2021.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

